The Nigerian army on Sunday said it had arrested a Boko Haram leader nine years after he was declared wanted. The suspect, Maje Lawan, was arrested at Banki, a town in the northern state of Borno after he infiltrated into an Internally Displaced Persons (IDPs) camp in the area. Mr Lawan is believed to be one of the right hand men of Boko Haram factional leader Abubakar Shekau. Army spokesman Brig Gen Texas Chukwu said the suspect, believed to be number 96 on the wanted list, was â€œundergoing preliminary investigation and will be handed over to the appropriate authority for further action." More than 25,000 people have died in the in the north-eastern states of Borno, Adamawa and Yobe since Boko Haram insurgency in 2009.   On Friday and Saturday, Katumbi was refused entry from Zambia as he tried to get home. Fall was largely due to the failure by member states to promote the region as a single investment